<item>
            <title>[MATH-1037] Distribution tests are mostly meaningless due to high tolerance</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MATH-1037</link>
                <project id="12310485" key="MATH">Commons Math</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The tolerance used for value comparison in &lt;tt&gt;IntegerDistributionAbstractTest&lt;/tt&gt; is &lt;tt&gt;1E-4&lt;/tt&gt;. However, most values being compared are much smaller, so they are considered equal even if they otherwise differ by orders of magnitude. For example, a typo in &lt;tt&gt;GeometricDistributionTest&lt;/tt&gt; puts 29 in the test points instead of 19, while the test probability value is correctly given for 19. The test passes, disregarding the fact that &lt;tt&gt;2.437439e-05&lt;/tt&gt; (test value for 19) and &lt;tt&gt;1.473826e-07&lt;/tt&gt; (actual value for 29) differ almost hundredfold.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment></environment>
